ral implications of the shift from the intimate café-concert to the spectacular music hall, before the talkies displaced both kinds of live performance altogether.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aMotion picture musicxHistory and criticismxFrance. 0aMotion picture musiczFrancexHistory and criticism. 0aMotion picturesxHistoryxFrance. 0aMotion pictureszFrancexHistory. 0aPopular musicxHistory and criticismxFrance. 0aPopular musiczFrancexHistory and criticism. 0aWomen singersxFrance. 0aWomen singerszFrance. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  a1930s.  abeauty.  abelle epoque music hall.  acafe concert.  acinema lovers.  acinemaphiles.  acultural implications.  acultural roles.  acultural studies.  afemale desire.  afemininity.  afilm and culture.  afilm historians.  afrance.  afrench cinema.  afrench culture.  afrench film.  agender roles.  agolden era.  amusic hall careers.  amusic.  aparis.  apopular entertainment.  apopular music.  arealist performance.  arealist singer.  asingers.  atheatre.  awomen in film.  awomens roles.  aworking class life.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093857140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520938571423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520938571/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles